Central Line-Associated Bloodstream infections (CLABSI) in California Hospitals

Introduction

The NHSN defines CLABSI as a laboratory-confirmed bloodstream infection that occurs in a patient who had a central venous catheter placed within 48 hours prior to the date of blood culture collection, with no other source of bacteremia or fungemia identified. This definition is based on monitoring rather than clinical presentation and does not stipulate any requirements regarding symptoms or signs of infection. Since it is often difficult to determine whether a bloodstream infection is related to the central venous catheter itself or to a secondary source of infection (such as an abdominal abscess or pneumonia), the NHSNâs definition of CLABSI may overestimate the true incidence of catheter-related infections. As a result, data interpretation can be more complex.

Question:How do CLABSI rates differ by type of hospital and by region in California?

#Rename Infections_Reported and Observed_infections to InfectNumber.
#Rename Pre_Infect.
read_and_rename <- function(file_path) {
  data <- fread(file_path)
  
 col_rename <- list(
    "Infections_Reported" = "InfectNumber",
    "Observed_infections" = "InfectNumber",
    "Observed_Infections" = "InfectNumber",
    "Infections_Predicted" = "Pred_Infect",
    "Predicted_infections" = "Pred_Infect",
    "Predicted_Infections" = "Pred_Infect",
    "Central_line_days" = "CentralLINE_Days",
    "Central_Line_Days" = "CentralLINE_Days",
    "Central_line_Days" = "CentralLINE_Days",
    "95%Confidence_Interval_Low_Limit" = "SIR_CI_95_Lower_Limit",
    "95%Confidence_Interval_Upper_Limit" = "SIR_CI_95_Upper_Limit",
    "Statistical_Interpretation" = "Comparison",
    "Hospital_Type" = "Facility_Type",
    "Hospital_Category_RiskAdjustment" = "Facility_Category"
  )
 for (col in names(data)) {
    if (col %in% names(col_rename)) {
      setnames(data, old = col, new = col_rename[[col]])
    }
  }
  
  return(data)
}
combined_data <- rbindlist(lapply(file_paths, read_and_rename), use.names = TRUE, fill = TRUE)

Data Dictionary.after reading the Description Data Dictionaryï¼I believe that âFacility IDâ is primarily a unique identifier used to track information about hospitals or healthcare facilities in the California Department of Public Health (CDPH) Electronic Licensing Management System (ELMS). It is important for data management and record keeping, but it has little impact on the analysis of central line-associated bloodstream infection (CLABSI) data itself and does not directly affect the analysis of infection rates or hospital performance. Therefore, I deleted it during the merging process. Clip_Adherence_Percent was reported in only four years, and On_Track_Toward_2020_Goal appeared only in 2017 and 2018, resulting in insufficient data. For this analysis, I have temporarily removed them.

clabsi_by_County <- cleaned_data1 %>%
  group_by(County) %>%
  summarize(
    Total_Infections = sum(InfectNumber, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Central_Line_Days = sum(CentralLINE_Days, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  mutate(CLABSI_Rate = (Total_Infections / Total_Central_Line_Days) * 1000)
